Title: Marvel's Doctor Strange Teaser Trailer
Comment: One of the coolest thing about this trailer is when we see Doctor Strange's soul being separated from his body. Not because of the act itself, but by the huge clue I think it gives. The color of his soul is orange. If this is so, it could give a huge clue to where the Soul Stone is. There's a character who's ability is to being able to see every soul. The color orange is very prevalent with this character and that's Heimdall. What if the Soul Stone is an actual soul, Heimdall's soul. It  would explain why the Infinity Gauntlet slot for the orange stone is not only bigger than the rest, but it's appearance is more like an energy source instead of a stone like the rest. Would make a sense as the Soul would be at the center of Space, Reality, Power, Mind and Time. If the stone on Doctor Strange necklace is an Infinity stone, then it's probably the Time Stone and not the Soul Stone like some have suggested. Heimdall's appearance in Thor's vision on Avengers: AoU made me suspicious, but now I'm almost certain this could be a thing. Other clues lie within Heimdall himself as his new armor has an orange stone in it, his eyes are orange, and his name starts with an H. That last one is super vague, but if Thanos name was meant as a clue to the location of all Stones, then maybe that's a thing. Tessaract, Aether, Orb, Scepter. We would be missing H and N. So Heimdall and Necklace would fit. Just a fun thought to have while we wait for the next movies. If this is the case though, Thor's third movie will be something to look forward to.

Title: Marvel's Doctor Strange Teaser Trailer
Comment:
Even ignoring the white-washing, this looks pretty boring. Pretty special effects are great, but the tone isn't anything special or unique. It has the inception, batman begins vibe, but without anything new. It has magic, but it doesn't feel grounded or real. The story wasn't really pinned down except dude gets hurt, finds a mentor, wants to learn magic, but it's usually fine to hold back in the first trailer. But this gets me as excited as Batman v. Superman's first trailer did, aka, bored as heck. I think it will be a pretty movie, but I think all the magic and personality went into Guardians of the Galaxy, all the action and drama went to Winter Soldier, and this is just not anything more than a few tropes and archetypes we've seen again and again strung together. 
Not ignoring the white-washing now, it is a red-flag for how sensitive the director/casting directors are to audience desires and perceptions. That same audience blindness I saw in the casting of Lex Luthor in Batman v. Superman, and on the Marvel side, in Joss Whedon's tap-twist in Age of Ultron. It's a bad sign for the characters, their nuances, and how they might develop. I'm not saying they couldn't cast Tilda Swinton, but they also (upping the supernatural and mind-bending factor) could have casted a few people as equally as her to play that one character, an Asian amongst them, and had them rotate equally to bend Strange's perceptions (and the audiences as well) as to who this person really is. Appearances are deceiving could have been a trope they played with, and baring casting an Asian (in an obviously Asian role) this is the second best option.

Title: Marvel's Doctor Strange Teaser Trailer
Comment:
I'll just copy a comment that I saw today on Facebook, because I think it's really informative (for people not knowing these things already), and well put:

Christopher Kidman:
"This will help those folks that have pointed out the Inception similarities. Doctor Strange is a mind-bending, psychedelic, and dark comic series. He is a practitioner of a mystic art form in which they can travel thru the very fabric of time and space. He can snap his fingers and transport The Avengers to another dimension. He's like the Bulk Beings in Interstellar. He can live and manipulate beyond the four dimensions we know. With powers like that, it would make him crucial for Infinity War. That "Inception" scene that you are referencing to is not the same as it was in Inception. It was quite different, just like it was in Upside Down. The visuals may be similar, but it's how I would expect a live action adaptation to look like. As much as I loved Inception, it wasn't all that original. It borrowed from The Thirteenth Floor, The Dark City, The Matrix, Videodrome, eXistenZ, and Paprika. A similar scene was in an earlier draft of X-Men: First Class, but the script was rewritten due to Inception's trailer being released. In a sense, all the mentioned films above were influenced by Doctor Strange comics, which have been around since 1963."

Title: Marvel's Doctor Strange Teaser Trailer
Comment: First Impressions: As long as they don't pull that Thor bs, and make magic "advanced technology," I'll be completely on bored with this movie. It seems to follow the comics well in terms of origin story. I am worried about how some actors will handle the strange/aloof/eccentric nature of their characters. Im hoping it's not a generic "superhero story;" being different is the only way this movie will work. Also the lack of a featured antagonist is worrying. Although, I'm glad that the trailer didn't do what every other trailer does, and give away 99% of the movie. Also, the settings look interesting. It is also refreshing to see these settings in the overplayed superhero movie genre. Also, I'm confused about how much, or how little the abstract nature of magic will be in the movie. All in all I'm very much intrigued by this movie, and excitedly anticipate it's release.
